Japan’s Stock Futures Fall on Report Toyota to Delay Forecast

-- B y   A k i k o   I k e d a   a n d   T o s h i r o   H a s e g a w a
-- 
2011-04-14T23:19:56Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-14/japanese-stock-futures-decline-after-report-toyota-will-delay-forecasts.html
Japanese stock futures fell after a
report  Toyota Motor Corp. (7203)  will delay its earnings forecast amid
earthquake damage and disruption of parts supplies. Australian
stocks futures rose as oil advanced.  American depositary receipts of Toyota, the world’s largest
automaker, dropped 0.4 percent from the closing share price in
Tokyo. Those of  Sony Corp. (6758) , Japan’s largest exporter of consumer
electronics, declined 0.5 percent. ADRs of  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP) ,
Australia’s No. 1 oil producer and the world’s biggest mining
company, rose 0.2 percent.  Futures on Japan’s  Nikkei 225 (NKY)  Stock Average expiring in
June closed at 9,620 in Chicago yesterday, compared with 9,650
in Osaka, Japan. They were bid in the pre-market at 9,610 in
Osaka, at 8:05 a.m. local time. Futures on  Australia ’s S&P/ASX
200 Index gained 0.1 percent today.  “Buying is tough in an environment where you don’t know
what the forecasts are going to be,” said Kazuhiro Takahashi, a
general manager at Tokyo-based Daiwa Securities Capital Markets
Co. “Right now investors are cautious about taking long-
positions.”  Futures on the Standard & Poor’s 500 Index increased 0.1
percent today. In  New York , the index rose less than 0.1 percent
yesterday, as the U.S. House of Representatives approved a
spending bill to avert a government shutdown.  Toyota Forecast Delay  The MSCI Asia Pacific Index lost 0.9 percent this year
through yesterday, compared with gains of 4.5 percent by the S&P
500 and 0.4 percent by the Stoxx Europe 600 Index. Stocks in the
Asian benchmark are valued at 13.2 times estimated earnings on
average, compared with 13.5 times for the  S&P 500  and 11.2 times
for the Stoxx 600.  Toyota won’t release its earnings forecasts for fiscal 2011
when it reports results for the 12 months ended March 31, the
Nikkei newspaper reported. Disruptions to supply chains in the
wake of last month’s earthquake and tsunami have made it
difficult for the automaker formulate production and sales plans,
the report said. Toyota and other Japanese companies usually
provide forecasts with earnings reports.  Crude oil for May delivery rose 0.9 percent to settle at
$108.11 a barrel in New York yesterday on reports that Saudi
Arabia, holder of the world’s largest oil reserves, reduced
output this month.  To contact the reporters on this story:
